Sub-Sahara Africa Stocks: KenolKobil, Kenya Commercial, Jubilee

-- B y   E r i c   O m b o k
-- 
2011-04-04T09:55:24Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-04/sub-sahara-africa-stocks-kenolkobil-kenya-commercial-jubilee.html
Kenya ’s All-Share Index increased
for a fourth day, adding 0.6 percent to 73.65 at 12:37 p.m. in
Nairobi.  The Nigerian Stock Exchange All-Share Index fell less than
0.1 percent to 24,747.61 at 10:53 a.m. in Lagos, according to
data compiled by Bloomberg.  Namibia ’s FTSE/ Namibia Overall Index (FTN098) 
retreated 0.1 percent to 884.3 at 11:38 a.m. in Windhoek. The
Ghana Stock Exchange Composite Index fell 0.5 percent to 1,062.9
at 9:53 in Accra, a second day of decreases. Mauritius’s market
was closed for a public holiday.  The following shares rose or fell in sub-Saharan  Africa ,
excluding  South Africa . Stock symbols are in parentheses.  KenolKobil Ltd. (KNOC KN) gained for a fourth day, adding
10 cents, or 1 percent, to 9.85 shillings. The Kenyan fuel
retailer with operations in nine African nations, which has a 25
percent share of the Kenyan oil market, plans to issue 300
million shares to increase capital, it said in a statement e-
mailed after the market closed on April 1.  Kenya Commercial Bank Ltd. (KNCB)  , the biggest lender by
outlets in the East African nation, jumped to its highest level
in 2 1/2 years, advancing 75 cents, or 3.1 percent, to 25
shillings after Business Daily reported it will open an
 investment-banking  unit within three months. Kenya Commercial is
re-entering investment banking after selling its Dyer & Blair
Investment Bank unit in 1983, Business Daily reported, citing
Deputy Chief Executive Officer Peter Munyiri.  Jubilee Holdings Ltd. (JBIC)  , an insurer with operations
in five African countries, jumped the most in almost 13 months,
rallying 20 cents, or 11 percent, to 200 shillings. Pretax
profit increased 84 percent to 2.53 billion shillings ($30.3
million) from 1.6 billion shillings in the year through
December, Chairman Nizar Juma said after close of the last
trading session on April 1.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Eric Ombok in Nairobi at 
 eombok@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Gavin Serkin at 
 gserkin@bloomberg.net  